North Sea wind farms deliver a good 21 percent more electricity
The wind power plants on the German North Sea have fed 11.51 terawatt hours of electricity into the grid in the first six months of the year.
This is a good 21 percent more than in the same period last year, the grid operator Tennet in Bayreuth reported.
Tennet is responsible for the transmission of the North Sea electricity to the mainland and the transmission through the German electricity grid.
The wind turbines on the Baltic Sea, which are not part of Tennet's grid area, have supplied a further 2.22 terawatt hours (TWh) of electricity.
Overall, wind power from the North and Baltic Sea thus comes to 13.73 TWh, compared to a good 11.64 TWh in the first half of 2019.
The wind harvest at sea accounts for almost 19 percent of the total wind power in Germany; that is about four percentage points more than a year ago.
New wind farms provide higher generation capacities
The increased contribution of offshore wind energy is due to higher generation capacities in addition to wind conditions, as new wind farms have been connected to the grid in the past twelve months.
If the 1270 wind farms in the North Sea were all running at full power at the same time, they could generate 6.7 gigawatts of electricity.
The transmission capacity is sufficient for this purpose; according to Tennet, it is 7.1 gigawatts.
By 2030, it is expected to rise to 17 gigawatts in the German North Sea.
"In Germany and the Netherlands, we will invest 20 billion euros in the expansion of offshore network connections by then," said Tennet Managing Director Tim Meyerjürgens.
In reality, wind farms cannot even use up their capacity at sea, but can reach around 40 percent.
The record day so far this year is 2 January, when the North Sea wind farms generated more than six gigawatts of electricity.
On average, the North Sea wind turbines produce about 2.5 to 3.0 gigawatts of electricity, which corresponds to three to four nuclear power plants.
This could supply electricity to almost seven million households.
